topics.title: Introduction
topics.description: Overview of the Darwin FPV Quad
topics.coverage_text:
Hello and welcome to the video. This is a quick video on this new quad from Darwin FPV.
This is the CineApe 25. Now I've looked at a few other quads from Darwin FPV and I'm always
impressed because unlike some of the other people out there making these kind of ready-to-fly things,
the Darwin FPV stuff is a little bit less expensive. So it's kind of in the price range
of a lot more pilots but they do put a lot of thought and love into these things and this
25 is the latest one. So I thought I'd get it in and we'll have a go. Now this is available in a

So it's been a while since I've reviewed an analog quad but lots of you pilots out there I know
are still flying analog. Other 60% of all my viewers last time we did a poll are still flying analog and
waiting for digital HD and maybe making a choice in the spring. So let me unbox this and go through

So the big thing with this is this is like that kind of big whoop style where it has a high strength
one-piece injection molded prop guard. Very useful because it means that you can bounce off stuff.

topics.title: FPV Performance
topics.description: Analysis of the analog FPV setup
topics.coverage_text:
I've been very happy flying much closer into obstacles with this knowing that if I hit something
it's just going to bounce off it rather than destroy a prop potentially snap an arm. Battery life claimed
on this is up to nine minutes. We'll see what that is in a moment. I think nine minutes is optimistic,
gentle flying potentially without any kind of action camera installed. So again this is the Darwin FPV
Cine Ape 25. It's an X style layout. Six bladed props. Wheelbase is 112 millimeters. Dimensions of this
thing isn't particularly big. It's a nice size for flying around large indoor environments and also
flying outside as well. So it's about 160 by 160 by 43 millimeters. Flight controller on this is an F411
base thing and it does have 30 amp 3 to 4S ESCs. I'm running mine on 4S here. Again as I said in the
introduction this happens to be the analog version. Comes with a Caddx ant. Not a fan of the ant
unfortunately but we'll see how it performs here in a moment with a 600 milliwatt analog VTX. But

topics.title: Conclusion
topics.coverage_text:
Basically auxiliary one arms it and puts it into angle so they're not expecting you to use horizon
even though you can flip and roll. On-screen display looks like this. I'd definitely come in here and move
things around. Everyone has their own particular way of doing it. Video transmitter for my analog version
here is all set up and the tables all loaded. It's pretty much ready to rock and roll. Again dump and
diff are down below if you want to go and have a look. In terms of flying. Flying is an awful lot of fun.
The noise level from those multi-related props is a little bit higher than I would like. It's very very
kind of a high wind buzz which does mean that even when it's a reasonable distance away from you
you can still hear it and if you blip the throttle then everyone in the field that you're in is going to hear it as well.
